dentity and social stratification continues to be a point of analysis.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These debates emphasize the complexity of post-colonial identity formation in the Philippines and the lasting effects of policies such as the Claveria Decree.</p>\n<h2>Comparative Perspectives: The Claveria Decree and Other Colonial Naming Policies</h2>\n<p>The Claveria Decree is not unique in colonial history. Similar naming policies have been implemented in various colonies worldwide to facilitate governance and control.</p>\n<h3>Comparison with Other Colonial Naming Systems</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>British India:</strong> The British colonial administration standardized surnames and naming conventions to improve census and tax records, though often less systematically than the Claveria Decree.</li>\n<li><strong>French Algeria:</strong> French authorities imposed French surnames or naming conventions on indigenous populations to assert control and promote assimilation.</li>\n<li><strong>Portuguese Colonies:</strong> In places like Brazil and Goa, Portuguese surnames became widespread due to missionary activity and colonial administration.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Such comparisons reveal common colonial strategies aimed at social control through identity regulation, with the Claveria Decree standing out for its detailed catalog and enforced implementation.</p>\n<h3>Distinct Features of the Claveria Decree Garcia</h3>\n<p>Unlike some colonial naming policies that were more ad hoc, the Claveria Decree featured:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A comprehensive alphabetical catalog of surnames.</li>\n<li>Mandatory adoption across provinces, with local officials overseeing compliance.</li>\n<li>Integration of Hispanic surnames regardless of ethnic or linguistic backgrounds.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These distinct features contributed to the decree’s lasting impact on Filipino society and identity.</p>\n<h2>Legal and Genealogical Implications of the Claveria Decree Garcia</h2>\n<p>For legal professionals and genealogists,